[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Analyzing JaCoCo coverage**\n\nI’m looking into why JaCoCo is showing a class method as not covered when the test results passed. Maybe it’s because that method is excluded or related to synthetic methods? I think inspecting the JaCoCo HTML report might be helpful.\n\nIt could also be that our workflow didn’t properly include the file since the tests were built beforehand. Additionally, if a class is already reachable, JaCoCo might filter it out during dynamic access reports, even if \"call site covered\" should catch any invocation. I'm curious to explore this further!\n\n**Exploring Class.forName behavior**\n\nI’m considering why Class.forName might not be capturing coverage as expected. Could it be that native substitution is folding it into a constant? Maybe using class$ with a class name that isn’t reachable plays a role, but does it really need dynamic metadata?\n\nIf Class.forName is called on a test class, the dynamic access report is supposed to note that, but could the target be getting filtered out? I'm also thinking about using a library class that isn't statically referenced in tests, yet I’d still need an assertion. This is a bit puzzling!\n\n**Inspecting Jacoco coverage**\n\nI think the TCK report likely only measures call sites from the code that's being tested. There might be a line like `class$(CsrfTokenFinder.groovy)` in the code, but if it's called via Method.invoke, then Jacoco coverage shows that the class$ method is covered. I'll need to check the Jacoco effective XML to get a clearer picture of how coverage is represented. Getting this right is crucial, so I'll proceed carefully!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_09e80d339dd84ba4016a281361f6488193a124a3811bb59f33\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqKBOPttGzEoxgjrzBIE4_9BxJS427RGKB6kK2Dq4Bh0JdWpSE83afMdvWTxUuRWs0LyQmm9dSZMi_N7EFd6QkNC5UM0i84iYnQl_M